# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ct-imaging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] CBCT has become increasingly important in treatment planning and diagnosis in implant dentistry, ENT, orthopedics, and interventional radiology (IR), among other things.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] Because of increased access to the technology, CBCT scanners are now widely used in dentistry, such as in the fields of oral surgery, endodontics and orthodontics.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] Integrated CBCT is also an important tool for patient positioning and verification in image-guided radiation therapy (IGRT).
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] During dental and orthodontic imaging, the CBCT scanner rotates around the patient's head, acquiring up to 600 distinct images.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] For interventional radiology, the patient is positioned offset to the table so that the region of interest is centered in the field of view for the cone beam.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] A single 200 degree rotation over the region of interest acquires a volumetric data set.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The scanning software collects the data and reconstructs it, producing what is termed a *digital volume* composed of three-dimensional voxels of anatomical data that can then be manipulated and visualized with specialized software.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] CBCT shares many similarities with traditional (fan beam) CT however there are important differences, particularly for reconstruction.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] CBCT has been described as the gold standard for imaging the oral and maxillofacial area.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] In the late 1990s, Dr Yoshinori Arai in Japan and Dr Piero Mozzo in Italy independently developed Cone Beam Computed Technology for oral and maxillofacial radiology.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The first commercial system (the NewTom 9000) was introduced in the European market in 1996 and into the US market in 2001, by Italian company Quantitative Radiology (also known as QR, based in Verona).
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] Cone beam CT using kilovoltage X-rays (as used for diagnostic, rather than therapeutic purposes) attached to a linear accelerator treatment machine was first developed in the late 1990s and early 2000s.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] Such systems have since become common on latest generation linacs.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] In the late 2010s CBCT also started to become available on-board particle therapy delivery systems.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] While CBCT with X-ray image intensifiers was experimented with in the late 1990s, it was not until the adoption of flat-panel X-ray detectors, with improved contrast and spatial resolution, that CBCT became practical for clinical use in interventional radiology procedures.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] Many fixed, and even mobile, C-arm fluoroscopy systems are now capable of CBCT acquisitions, in addition to traditional planar fluoroscopy.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] CBCT provides image guidance during interventional radiology procedures for conditions such as knee osteoarthritis, benign prostatic hyperplasia, and hepatocellular carcinoma.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The most significant advantage of the CBCT in Endodontics is that it can show critical root canal anatomical features that conventional intraoral or panoramic images cannot.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] According to the American Association of Endodontics, there are numerous specific situations in which 3D images produced by CBCT enhance diagnosis and influence treatment, and its use cannot be disputed over conventional intraoral radiology based on ALARA principles.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] A dental cone beam scan offers useful information when it comes to the assessment and planning of surgical implants.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The American Academy of Oral and Maxillofacial Radiology (AAOMR) suggests cone-beam CT as the preferred method for presurgical assessment of dental implant sites.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] As a 3D rendition, CBCT offers an undistorted view of the dentition that can be used to accurately visualize both erupted and non-erupted teeth, tooth root orientation and anomalous structures, that conventional 2D radiography cannot.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The CBCT scanner offers undistorted views of the extremities.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] One advantage of orthopedic CBCT is the ability to take weight bearing images of the lower extremities.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] In the realm of the foot and ankle particularly, weight bearing CBCT is gaining momentum due to its ability to combine 3 dimensional and weight bearing information which are of the utmost importance in diagnosis and surgical planning.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The preferred term used for CBCT in the lower limb is thus WBCT for Weight Bearing CT following the first scientific publications on the subject.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] Image-guided radiation therapy is a form of external beam radiotherapy where the patient is positioned with the organs to be treated accurately matched in position to the treatment field, to reduce the dose to nearby organs which are not being treated.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The images may also be used to check for other requirements of some types of treatment, such as full or empty bladder, empty rectum, etc.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The same cone beam beam source and detector can alternatively be used to take simple X-ray positioning images if the organ shows particularly well on X-ray or if Fiducial markers have been inserted into the organ.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The CBCT scanner is mounted on a C-arm fluoroscopy unit in the interventional radiology (IR) suite, which offers real time imaging with a stationary patient.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] This eliminates the time needed to transfer a patient from the angiography suite to a conventional computed tomography scanner and facilitates a broad spectrum of applications of CBCT during IR procedures.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The clinical applications of CBCT in IR include treatment planning, device or implant positioning and assessment, intra-procedural localization, and assessment of procedure endpoints.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] CBCT is useful as a primary and supplemental form of imaging.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] It is an excellent adjunct to DSA and fluoroscopy for soft tissue and vascular visibility during complex procedures.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The use of CBCT before fluoroscopy potentially reduces patient radiation exposure.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] Cone beam CT is used for material analysis, metrology, and nondestructive testing in the manufacturing sector.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] Cone beam CT is also inspect and detect defects of tiny sizes, such as internal pitting corrosion or cracks of an object in quality control.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] Cone beam reconstruction algorithms are similar to typical tomographic reconstruction algorithms, and methods such as filtered backprojection or iterative reconstruction may be used.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] However, since the reconstruction is three-dimensional, modifications such as the FDK algorithm may be needed.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] Total radiation doses from 3D dental CBCT exams are 96% lower than conventional CT exams, but deliver 5-16x more radiation than standard dental 2D x-ray (OPG).
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The time of exposure in CBCT is also comparatively less when compared to conventional CT.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] CBCT use is only lightly regulated in the US.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The recommended standard of care is to use the smallest possible field of view (FOV), the smallest voxel size, the lowest mA setting and the shortest exposure time in conjunction with a pulsed exposure mode of acquisition.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] International organisations such as the World Health Organization and ICRP, as well as many local bodies and legislation, encourage the idea of justification for all medical exposures, where risks and benefits must be weighed up before a procedure goes ahead.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] There are a number of drawbacks of CBCT technology over that of CT scans, such as increased susceptibility to movement artifacts (in first generation machines) and to the lack of appropriate bone density determination.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The Hounsfield scale is used to measure radiodensity and, in reference to CT scans, can provide an accurate absolute density for the type of tissue depicted.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] Although some authors have supported the use of CBCT technology to evaluate bone density by measuring HU, such support is provided erroneously because scanned regions of the same density in the skull can have a different grayscale value in the reconstructed CBCT dataset.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] Dental CBCT systems do not employ a standardized system for scaling the grey levels that represent the reconstructed density values and, as such, they are arbitrary and do not allow for assessment of bone quality.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] In the absence of such a standardization, it is difficult to interpret the grey levels or impossible to compare the values resulting from different machines.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] While there is a general acknowledgment that this deficiency exists with CBCT systems (in that they do not correctly display HU), there has been little research conducted to attempt to correct this deficiency.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] With time, further advancements in CBCT reconstruction algorithms will allow for improved area detectors, and this, together with enhanced postprocessing, will likely solve or reduce this problem.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] A method for establishing attenuation coefficients with which actual HU values can be derived from CBCT "HU" values was published in 2010 and further research is currently underway to perfect this method *in vivo*.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] While the practicality of CBCT fosters its increasing application in IR, technical limitations hinder its integration into the field.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The two most significant factors that affect successful integration are image quality and time (for set up, image acquisition, and image reconstruction).
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] Compared to multidetector computed tomography (MDCT), the wider collimation in CBCT leads to increased scatter radiation and degradation of image quality as demonstrated by artifacts and decreased contrast-to-noise ratio.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The temporal resolution of cesium iodide detectors in CBCT slows data acquisition time to approximately 5 to 20 seconds, which increases motion artifacts.
[src:ct-imaging/cone-beam-computed-tomography] The time required for image reconstruction takes longer for CBCT (1 minute) compared to MDCT (real time) due to the computationally demanding cone beam reconstruction algorithms.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] A **computed tomography scan** (**CT scan**), formerly known in a more rudimentary state as **computed axial tomography scan** (**CAT scan**), is a medical imaging technique used to obtain detailed internal images of the body.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The personnel that perform CT scans are called radiographers or radiology technologists.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT scanners use a rotating X-ray tube and a row of detectors placed in a gantry to measure X-ray attenuations by different tissues inside the body.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The multiple X-ray measurements taken from different angles are then processed on a computer using tomographic reconstruction algorithms to produce tomographic (cross-sectional) images (virtual "slices") of a body.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT scans can be used in patients with metallic implants or pacemakers, for whom magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) is contraindicated.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Since its development in the 1970s, CT scanning has proven to be a versatile imaging technique.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] While CT is most prominently used in medical diagnosis, it can also be used to form images of non-living objects.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The 1979 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine was awarded jointly to British electrical engineer Godfrey Hounsfield and South African-American physicist Allan MacLeod Cormack "for the development of computer-assisted tomography".
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] On the basis of image acquisition and procedures, various types of scanners are available in the market.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Sequential CT, also known as step-and-shoot CT, is a type of scanning method in which the CT table moves stepwise.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The table increments to a particular location and then stops, followed by rotation of the X-ray tube and acquisition of a slice.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The table then increments again, and another slice is taken.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The table movement stops while taking slices, which results in an increased scan duration.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Spinning tube, commonly called spiral CT, or helical CT, is an imaging technique in which an entire X-ray tube is spun around the central axis of the area being scanned.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] These are the dominant type of scanners on the market because they have been manufactured longer and offer a lower cost of production and purchase.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The main limitation of this type of CT is the bulk and inertia of the equipment (X-ray tube assembly and detector array on the opposite side of the circle) which limits the speed at which the equipment can spin.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Some designs use two X-ray sources and detector arrays offset by an angle, as a technique to improve temporal resolution.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Electron beam tomography (EBT) is a specific form of CT in which a large enough X-ray tube is constructed so that only the path of the electrons, travelling between the cathode and anode of the X-ray tube, are spun using deflection coils.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This type had a major advantage since sweep speeds can be much faster, allowing for less blurry imaging of moving structures, such as the heart and arteries.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Fewer scanners of this design have been produced when compared with spinning tube types, mainly due to the higher cost associated with building a much larger X-ray tube and detector array and limited anatomical coverage.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Dual energy CT, also known as spectral CT, is an advancement of computed Tomography in which two energies are used to create two sets of data.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] A dual energy CT may employ dual source, single source with dual detector layer, single source with energy switching methods to get two different sets of data.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT perfusion imaging is a specific form of CT to assess flow through blood vessels whilst injecting a contrast agent.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Blood flow, blood transit time, and organ blood volume, can all be calculated with reasonable sensitivity and specificity.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This type of CT may be used on the heart, although sensitivity and specificity for detecting abnormalities are still lower than for other forms of CT.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This may also be used on the brain, where CT perfusion imaging can often detect poor brain perfusion well before it is detected using a conventional spiral CT scan.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This is better for stroke diagnosis than other CT types.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Thus, functional imaging obtained by PET, which depicts the spatial distribution of metabolic or biochemical activity in the body can be more precisely aligned or correlated with anatomic imaging obtained by CT scanning.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] PET-CT gives both anatomical and functional details of an organ under examination and is helpful in detecting different type of cancers.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Since its introduction in the 1970s, CT has become an important tool in medical imaging to supplement conventional X-ray imaging and medical ultrasonography.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] It has more recently been used for preventive medicine or screening for disease, for example, CT colonography for people with a high risk of colon cancer, or full-motion heart scans for people with a high risk of heart disease.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Several institutions offer full-body scans for the general population although this practice goes against the advice and official position of many professional organizations in the field primarily due to the radiation dose applied.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The use of CT scans has increased dramatically.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] An estimated 72 million scans were performed in the United States in 2007 and more than 80 million in 2015.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT scanning of the head is typically used to detect infarction (stroke), tumors, calcifications, haemorrhage, and bone trauma.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Of the above, hypodense (dark) structures can indicate edema and infarction, hyperdense (bright) structures indicate calcifications and haemorrhage and bone trauma can be seen as disjunction in bone windows.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Tumors can be detected by the swelling and anatomical distortion they cause, or by surrounding edema.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT scanning of the head is also used in CT-guided stereotactic surgery and radiosurgery for treatment of intracranial tumors, arteriovenous malformations, and other surgically treatable conditions using a device known as the N-localizer.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Contrast CT is generally the initial study of choice for neck masses in adults.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT of the thyroid plays an important role in the evaluation of thyroid cancer.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT scans often incidentally find thyroid abnormalities, and so is often the preferred investigation modality for thyroid abnormalities.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] A CT scan can be used for detecting both acute and chronic changes in the lung parenchyma, the tissue of the lungs.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] It is particularly helpful because normal two-dimensional X-rays do not show such defects.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] A variety of techniques are used, depending on the suspected abnormality.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] For evaluation of chronic interstitial processes such as emphysema, and fibrosis, thin sections with high spatial frequency reconstructions are used; often scans are performed both on inspiration and expiration.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This special technique is called high resolution CT that produces a sampling of the lung, and not continuous images.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Bronchial wall thickening can be seen on lung CTs and generally (but not always) implies inflammation of the bronchi.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] An incidentally found nodule in the absence of symptoms (sometimes referred to as an incidentaloma) may raise concerns that it might represent a tumor, either benign or malignant.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Perhaps persuaded by fear, patients and doctors sometimes agree to an intensive schedule of CT scans, sometimes up to every three months and beyond the recommended guidelines, in an attempt to do surveillance on the nodules.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] However, established guidelines advise that patients without a prior history of cancer and whose solid nodules have not grown over a two-year period are unlikely to have any malignant cancer.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] For this reason, and because no research provides supporting evidence that intensive surveillance gives better outcomes, and because of risks associated with having CT scans, patients should not receive CT screening in excess of those recommended by established guidelines.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Computed tomography angiography (CTA) is a type of contrast CT to visualize the arteries and veins throughout the body.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This ranges from arteries serving the brain to those bringing blood to the lungs, kidneys, arms and legs.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] An example of this type of exam is CT pulmonary angiogram (CTPA) used to diagnose pulmonary embolism (PE).
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] It employs computed tomography and an iodine-based contrast agent to obtain an image of the pulmonary arteries.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT scans can reduce the risk of angiography by providing clinicians with more information about the positioning and number of clots prior to the procedure.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] A CT scan of the heart is performed to gain knowledge about cardiac or coronary anatomy.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Traditionally, cardiac CT scans are used to detect, diagnose, or follow up coronary artery disease.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] More recently CT has played a key role in the fast-evolving field of transcatheter structural heart interventions, more specifically in the transcatheter repair and replacement of heart valves.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] To better visualize the anatomy, post-processing of the images is common.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Most common are multiplanar reconstructions (MPR) and volume rendering.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] For more complex anatomies and procedures, such as heart valve interventions, a true 3D reconstruction or a 3D print is created based on these CT images to gain a deeper understanding.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT is an accurate technique for diagnosis of abdominal diseases such as Crohn's disease, GIT bleeding, and diagnosis and staging of cancer, as well as follow-up after cancer treatment to assess response.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] It is commonly used to investigate acute abdominal pain.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Non-contrast-enhanced CT scans are the gold standard for diagnosing kidney stone disease.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] They allow clinicians to estimate the size, volume, and density of stones, helping to guide further treatment; with size being especially important in predicting the time to spontaneous passage of a stone.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] For the axial skeleton and extremities, CT is often used to image complex fractures, especially ones around joints, because of its ability to reconstruct the area of interest in multiple planes.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Fractures, ligamentous injuries, and dislocations can easily be recognized with a 0.2 mm resolution.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] With modern dual-energy CT scanners, new areas of use have been established, such as aiding in the diagnosis of gout.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT is used in biomechanics to quickly reveal the geometry, anatomy, density and elastic moduli of biological tissues.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Industrial CT scanning (industrial computed tomography) is a process which uses X-ray equipment to produce 3D representations of components both externally and internally.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Industrial CT scanning has been used in many areas of industry for internal inspection of components.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Some of the key uses for CT scanning have been flaw detection, failure analysis, metrology, assembly analysis, image-based finite element methods and reverse engineering applications.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT scanning is also employed in the imaging and conservation of museum artifacts.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Its usage in airport security pioneered at Shannon Airport in March 2022 has ended the ban on liquids over 100 ml there, a move that Heathrow Airport plans for a full roll-out on 1 December 2022 and the TSA spent $781.2 million on an order for over 1,000 scanners, ready to go live in the summer.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] X-ray CT is used in geological studies to quickly reveal materials inside a drill core.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Dense minerals such as pyrite and barite appear brighter and less dense components such as clay appear dull in CT images.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Traditional methods of studying fossils are often destructive, such as the use of thin sections and physical preparation.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] X-ray CT is used in paleontology to non-destructively visualize fossils in 3D.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] For example, we can look at fragile structures that might never otherwise be able to be studied.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] In addition, one can freely move around models of fossils in virtual 3D space to inspect it without damaging the fossil.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] X-ray CT and micro-CT can also be used for the conservation and preservation of objects of cultural heritage.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] For many fragile objects, direct research and observation can be damaging and can degrade the object over time.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Using CT scans, conservators and researchers are able to determine the material composition of the objects they are exploring, such as the position of ink along the layers of a scroll, without any additional harm.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] These scans have been optimal for research focused on the workings of the Antikythera mechanism or the text hidden inside the charred outer layers of the En-Gedi Scroll.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] However, they are not optimal for every object subject to these kinds of research questions, as there are certain artifacts like the Herculaneum papyri in which the material composition has very little variation along the inside of the object.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] After scanning these objects, computational methods can be employed to examine the insides of these objects, as was the case with the virtual unwrapping of the En-Gedi scroll and the Herculaneum papyri.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Micro-CT has also proved useful for analyzing more recent artifacts such as still-sealed historic correspondence that employed the technique of letterlocking (complex folding and cuts) that provided a "tamper-evident locking mechanism".
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Further examples of use cases in archaeology is imaging the contents of sarcophagi or ceramics.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Recently, CWI in Amsterdam has collaborated with Rijksmuseum to investigate art object inside details in the framework called IntACT.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Varied types of fungus can degrade wood to different degrees, one Belgium research group has used X-ray CT 3 dimension with sub-micron resolution unveiled fungi can penetrate micropores of 0.6 μm under certain conditions.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Sawmills use industrial CT scanners to detect round defects, for instance knots, to improve total value of timber productions.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Most sawmills are planning to incorporate this robust detection tool to improve productivity in the long run, however initial investment cost is high.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Technically, all volume renderings become projections when viewed on a 2-dimensional display, making the distinction between projections and volume renderings a bit vague.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The epitomes of volume rendering models feature a mix of for example coloring and shading in order to create realistic and observable representations.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Two-dimensional CT images are conventionally rendered so that the view is as though looking up at it from the patient's feet.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Hence, the left side of the image is to the patient's right and vice versa, while anterior in the image also is the patient's anterior and vice versa.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This left-right interchange corresponds to the view that physicians generally have in reality when positioned in front of patients.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Pixels in an image obtained by CT scanning are displayed in terms of relative radiodensity.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The pixel itself is displayed according to the mean attenuation of the tissue(s) that it corresponds to on a scale from +3,071 (most attenuating) to −1,024 (least attenuating) on the Hounsfield scale.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] A pixel is a two dimensional unit based on the matrix size and the field of view.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] When the CT slice thickness is also factored in, the unit is known as a voxel, which is a three-dimensional unit.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Water has an attenuation of 0 Hounsfield units (HU), while air is −1,000 HU, cancellous bone is typically +400 HU, and cranial bone can reach 2,000 HU.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The attenuation of metallic implants depends on the atomic number of the element used: Titanium usually has an amount of +1000 HU, iron steel can completely block the X-ray and is, therefore, responsible for well-known line-artifacts in computed tomograms.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Artifacts are caused by abrupt transitions between low- and high-density materials, which results in data values that exceed the dynamic range of the processing electronics.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT data sets have a very high dynamic range which must be reduced for display or printing.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This is typically done via a process of "windowing", which maps a range (the "window") of pixel values to a grayscale ramp.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] For example, CT images of the brain are commonly viewed with a window extending from 0 HU to 80 HU.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Pixel values of 0 and lower, are displayed as black; values of 80 and higher are displayed as white; values within the window are displayed as a gray intensity proportional to position within the window.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The window used for display must be matched to the X-ray density of the object of interest, in order to optimize the visible detail.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Window width and window level parameters are used to control the windowing of a scan.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Multiplanar reconstruction (MPR) is the process of converting data from one anatomical plane (usually transverse) to other planes.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] It can be used for thin slices as well as projections.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Multiplanar reconstruction is possible as present CT scanners provide almost isotropic resolution.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The spine is frequently examined with it.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] An image of the spine in axial plane can only show one vertebral bone at a time and cannot show its relation with other vertebral bones.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] By reformatting the data in other planes, visualization of the relative position can be achieved in sagittal and coronal plane.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] New software allows the reconstruction of data in non-orthogonal (oblique) planes, which help in the visualization of organs which are not in orthogonal planes.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] It is better suited for visualization of the anatomical structure of the bronchi as they do not lie orthogonal to the direction of the scan.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Curved-plane reconstruction (or curved planar reformation = CPR) is performed mainly for the evaluation of vessels.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This type of reconstruction helps to straighten the bends in a vessel, thereby helping to visualize a whole vessel in a single image or in multiple images.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] After a vessel has been "straightened", measurements such as cross-sectional area and length can be made.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This is helpful in preoperative assessment of a surgical procedure.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] For 2D projections used in radiation therapy for quality assurance and planning of external beam radiotherapy, including digitally reconstructed radiographs, see Beam's eye view.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] A threshold value of radiodensity is set by the operator (e.g., a level that corresponds to bone).
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] With the help of edge detection image processing algorithms a 3D model can be constructed from the initial data and displayed on screen.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Various thresholds can be used to get multiple models, each anatomical component such as muscle, bone and cartilage can be differentiated on the basis of different colours given to them.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] However, this mode of operation cannot show interior structures.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Surface rendering is limited technique as it displays only the surfaces that meet a particular threshold density, and which are towards the viewer.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] However, In volume rendering, transparency, colours and shading are used which makes it easy to present a volume in a single image.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] For example, Pelvic bones could be displayed as semi-transparent, so that, even viewing at an oblique angle one part of the image does not hide another.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] An important issue within radiology today is how to reduce the radiation dose during CT examinations without compromising the image quality.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] In general, higher radiation doses result in higher-resolution images, while lower doses lead to increased image noise and unsharp images.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] However, increased dosage raises the adverse side effects, including the risk of radiation-induced cancer – a four-phase abdominal CT gives the same radiation dose as 300 chest X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Several methods that can reduce the exposure to ionizing radiation during a CT scan exist.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Individualize the examination and adjust the radiation dose to the body type and body organ examined.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Different body types and organs require different amounts of radiation.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Higher resolution is not always suitable, such as detection of small pulmonary masses.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Streaks are often seen around materials that block most X-rays, such as metal or bone.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This type of artifact commonly occurs in the posterior fossa of the brain, or if there are metal implants.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The streaks can be reduced using newer reconstruction techniques.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Approaches such as metal artifact reduction (MAR) can also reduce this artifact.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] images with special software such as GSI (Gemstone Spectral Imaging).
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] It is due to the scanner being unable to differentiate between a small amount of high-density material (e.g., bone) and a larger amount of lower density (e.g., cartilage).
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The reconstruction assumes that the X-ray attenuation within each voxel is homogeneous; this may not be the case at sharp edges.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] voxels, which have a much lower out-of-plane resolution, than in-plane resolution.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This can be partially overcome by scanning using thinner slices, or an isotropic acquisition on a modern scanner.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Probably the most common mechanical artifact, the image of one or many "rings" appears within an image.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] They are usually caused by the variations in the response from individual elements in a two dimensional X-ray detector due to defect or miscalibration.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Ring artifacts can largely be reduced by intensity normalization, also referred to as flat field correction.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Remaining rings can be suppressed by a transformation to polar space, where they become linear stripes.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] A comparative evaluation of ring artefact reduction on X-ray tomography images showed that the method of Sijbers and Postnov can effectively suppress ring artefacts.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This appears as grain on the image and is caused by a low signal to noise ratio.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This occurs more commonly when a thin slice thickness is used.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] It can also occur when the power supplied to the X-ray tube is insufficient to penetrate the anatomy.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Streaking appearances can occur when the detectors intersect the reconstruction plane.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This can be reduced with filters or a reduction in pitch.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This can give a "cupped appearance" when grayscale is visualized as height.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] It occurs because conventional sources, like X-ray tubes emit a polychromatic spectrum.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Because of this, the mean energy of the spectrum increases when passing the object, often described as getting "harder".
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This leads to an effect increasingly underestimating material thickness, if not corrected.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Many algorithms exist to correct for this artifact.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] They can be divided into mono- and multi-material methods.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT scanning has several advantages over traditional two-dimensional medical radiography.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] First, CT eliminates the superimposition of images of structures outside the area of interest.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Second, CT scans have greater image resolution, enabling examination of finer details.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT can distinguish between tissues that differ in radiographic density by 1% or less.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Third, CT scanning enables multiplanar reformatted imaging: scan data can be visualized in the transverse (or axial), coronal, or sagittal plane, depending on the diagnostic task.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The improved resolution of CT has permitted the development of new investigations.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] For example, CT angiography avoids the invasive insertion of a catheter.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT scanning can perform a virtual colonoscopy with greater accuracy and less discomfort for the patient than a traditional colonoscopy.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Virtual colonography is far more accurate than a barium enema for detection of tumors and uses a lower radiation dose.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT is a moderate-to-high radiation diagnostic technique.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The radiation dose for a particular examination depends on multiple factors: volume scanned, patient build, number and type of scan protocol, and desired resolution and image quality.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Two helical CT scanning parameters, tube current and pitch, can be adjusted easily and have a profound effect on radiation.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT scanning is more accurate than two-dimensional radiographs in evaluating anterior interbody fusion, although they may still over-read the extent of fusion.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The radiation used in CT scans can damage body cells, including DNA molecules, which can lead to radiation-induced cancer.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The radiation doses received from CT scans is variable.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Compared to the lowest dose X-ray techniques, CT scans can have 100 to 1,000 times higher dose than conventional X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] However, a lumbar spine X-ray has a similar dose as a head CT.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Articles in the media often exaggerate the relative dose of CT by comparing the lowest-dose X-ray techniques (chest X-ray) with the highest-dose CT techniques.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] In general, a routine abdominal CT has a radiation dose similar to three years of average background radiation.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Large scale population-based studies have consistently demonstrated that low dose radiation from CT scans has impacts on cancer incidence in a variety of cancers.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] For example, in a large population-based Australian cohort it was found that up to 3.7% of brain cancers were caused by CT scan radiation.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Some experts project that in the future, between three and five percent of all cancers would result from medical imaging.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] An Australian study of 10.9 million people reported that the increased incidence of cancer after CT scan exposure in this cohort was mostly due to irradiation.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] In this group, one in every 1,800 CT scans was followed by an excess cancer.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] If the lifetime risk of developing cancer is 40% then the absolute risk rises to 40.05% after a CT.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The risks of CT scan radiation are especially important in patients undergoing recurrent CT scans within a short time span of one to five years.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This creates an important issue of cancer risk to these patients.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Moreover, a highly significant finding that was previously unreported is that some patients received >100 mSv dose from CT scans in a single day, which counteracts existing criticisms some investigators may have on the effects of protracted versus acute exposure.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] There are contrarian views and the debate is ongoing.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Some studies have shown that publications indicating an increased risk of cancer from typical doses of body CT scans are plagued with serious methodological limitations and several highly improbable results, concluding that no evidence indicates such low doses cause any long-term harm.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] One study estimated that as many as 0.4% of cancers in the United States resulted from CT scans, and that this may have increased to as much as 1.5 to 2% based on the rate of CT use in 2007.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Others dispute this estimate, as there is no consensus that the low levels of radiation used in CT scans cause damage.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Lower radiation doses are used in many cases, such as in the investigation of renal colic.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] A person's age plays a significant role in the subsequent risk of cancer.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Estimated lifetime cancer mortality risks from an abdominal CT of a one-year-old is 0.1%, or 1:1000 scans.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The risk for someone who is 40 years old is half that of someone who is 20 years old with substantially less risk in the elderly.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The International Commission on Radiological Protection estimates that the risk to a fetus being exposed to 10 mGy (a unit of radiation exposure) increases the rate of cancer before 20 years of age from 0.03% to 0.04% (for reference a CT pulmonary angiogram exposes a fetus to 4 mGy).
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] A 2012 review did not find an association between medical radiation and cancer risk in children noting however the existence of limitations in the evidences over which the review is based.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT scans can be performed with different settings for lower exposure in children with most manufacturers of CT scans as of 2007 having this function built in.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Furthermore, certain conditions can require children to be exposed to multiple CT scans.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Current recommendations are to inform patients of the risks of CT scanning.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] However, employees of imaging centers tend not to communicate such risks unless patients ask.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] In the United States half of CT scans are contrast CTs using intravenously injected radiocontrast agents.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The most common reactions from these agents are mild, including nausea, vomiting, and an itching rash.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Severe life-threatening reactions may rarely occur.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Overall reactions occur in 1 to 3% with nonionic contrast and 4 to 12% of people with ionic contrast.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Skin rashes may appear within a week to 3% of people.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The old radiocontrast agents caused anaphylaxis in 1% of cases while the newer, low-osmolar agents cause reactions in 0.01–0.04% of cases.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Death occurs in about 2 to 30 people per 1,000,000 administrations, with newer agents being safer.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] There is a higher risk of mortality in those who are female, elderly or in poor health, usually secondary to either anaphylaxis or acute kidney injury.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The contrast agent may induce contrast-induced nephropathy.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This occurs in 2 to 7% of people who receive these agents, with greater risk in those who have preexisting kidney failure, preexisting diabetes, or reduced intravascular volume.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] People with mild kidney impairment are usually advised to ensure full hydration for several hours before and after the injection.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] For moderate kidney failure, the use of iodinated contrast should be avoided; this may mean using an alternative technique instead of CT.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] In addition to the use of intravenous contrast, orally administered contrast agents are frequently used when examining the abdomen.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] These are frequently the same as the intravenous contrast agents, merely diluted to approximately 10% of the concentration.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] However, oral alternatives to iodinated contrast exist, such as very dilute (0.5–1% w/v) barium sulfate suspensions.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Dilute barium sulfate has the advantage that it does not cause allergic-type reactions or kidney failure, but cannot be used in patients with suspected bowel perforation or suspected bowel injury, as leakage of barium sulfate from damaged bowel can cause fatal peritonitis.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Side effects from contrast agents, administered intravenously in some CT scans, might impair kidney performance in patients with kidney disease, although this risk is now believed to be lower than previously thought.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The table reports average radiation exposures; however, there can be a wide variation in radiation doses between similar scan types, where the highest dose could be as much as 22 times higher than the lowest dose.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] A typical plain film X-ray involves radiation dose of 0.01 to 0.15 mGy, while a typical CT can involve 10–20 mGy for specific organs, and can go up to 80 mGy for certain specialized CT scans.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] For purposes of comparison, the world average dose rate from naturally occurring sources of background radiation is 2.4 mSv per year, equal for practical purposes in this application to 2.4 mGy per year.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] While there is some variation, most people (99%) received less than 7 mSv per year as background radiation.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Medical imaging as of 2007 accounted for half of the radiation exposure of those in the United States with CT scans making up two thirds of this amount.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] In the United Kingdom it accounts for 15% of radiation exposure.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The average radiation dose from medical sources is ≈0.6 mSv per person globally as of 2007.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Those in the nuclear industry in the United States are limited to doses of 50 mSv a year and 100 mSv every 5 years.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Lead is the main material used by radiography personnel for shielding against scattered X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The radiation dose reported in the gray or mGy unit is proportional to the amount of energy that the irradiated body part is expected to absorb, and the physical effect (such as DNA double strand breaks) on the cells' chemical bonds by X-ray radiation is proportional to that energy.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The sievert unit is used in the report of the effective dose.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Thus, as is shown in the table above, the actual radiation that is absorbed by a scanned body part is often much larger than the effective dose suggests.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] A specific measure, termed the computed tomography dose index (CTDI), is commonly used as an estimate of the radiation absorbed dose for tissue within the scan region, and is automatically computed by medical CT scanners.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The equivalent dose is the effective dose of a case, in which the whole body would actually absorb the same radiation dose, and the sievert unit is used in its report.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] In the case of non-uniform radiation, or radiation given to only part of the body, which is common for CT examinations, using the local equivalent dose alone would overstate the biological risks to the entire organism.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The added lifetime risk of developing cancer by a single abdominal CT of 8 mSv is estimated to be 0.05%, or 1 one in 2,000.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Because of increased susceptibility of fetuses to radiation exposure, the radiation dosage of a CT scan is an important consideration in the choice of medical imaging in pregnancy.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] In October, 2009, the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) initiated an investigation of brain perfusion CT (PCT) scans, based on radiation burns caused by incorrect settings at one particular facility for this particular type of CT scan.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Over 200 patients were exposed to radiation at approximately eight times the expected dose for an 18-month period; over 40% of them lost patches of hair.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This event prompted a call for increased CT quality assurance programs.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] It was noted that "while unnecessary radiation exposure should be avoided, a medically needed CT scan obtained with appropriate acquisition parameter has benefits that outweigh the radiation risks." Similar problems have been reported at other centers.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] These incidents are believed to be due to human error.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] CT scan procedures vary according to the type of study and the organ being imaged.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The patient lies supine on the CT table, which is mechanically centered based on the target anatomical region.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] An intravenous (IV) line is established if a contrast-enhanced CT is required.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] After programming the proper volume and flow rate of the contrast media into the pressure injector, a preliminary "scout" image (topogram) is taken to localize the anatomy and plan the exact scan boundaries.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Once the scan parameters are confirmed, the contrast agent is administered.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The acquired raw data is computationally reconstructed according to the specific clinical study, and targeted windowing is applied to maximize tissue contrast for diagnostic interpretation.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Patient preparation may vary according to the type of scan.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The general patient preparation includes.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Removal of metallic objects and jewelry from the region of interest.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Changing to the hospital gown according to hospital protocol.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Checking of kidney function, especially creatinine and urea levels (in case of CECT).
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Computed tomography operates by using an X-ray generator that rotates around the object; X-ray detectors are positioned on the opposite side of the circle from the X-ray source.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] As the X-rays pass through the patient, they are attenuated differently by various tissues according to the tissue density.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] A visual representation of the raw data obtained is called a sinogram, yet it is not sufficient for interpretation.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Once the scan data has been acquired, the data must be processed using a form of tomographic reconstruction, which produces a series of cross-sectional images.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] These cross-sectional images are made up of small units of pixels or voxels.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Water has an attenuation of 0 Hounsfield units (HU), while air is −1,000 HU, cancellous bone is typically +400 HU, and cranial bone can reach 2,000 HU or more (os temporale) and can cause artifacts.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The attenuation of metallic implants depends on the atomic number of the element used: Titanium usually has an amount of +1000 HU, iron steel can completely extinguish the X-ray and is, therefore, responsible for well-known line-artifacts in computed tomograms.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Initially, the images generated in CT scans were in the transverse (axial) anatomical plane, perpendicular to the long axis of the body.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Modern scanners allow the scan data to be reformatted as images in other planes.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Digital geometry processing can generate a three-dimensional image of an object inside the body from a series of two-dimensional radiographic images taken by rotation around a fixed axis.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] These cross-sectional images are widely used for medical diagnosis and therapy.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Contrast media used for X-ray CT, as well as for plain film X-ray, are called radiocontrasts.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Radiocontrasts for CT are, in general, iodine-based.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This is useful to highlight structures such as blood vessels that otherwise would be difficult to delineate from their surroundings.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Using contrast material can also help to obtain functional information about tissues.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Often, images are taken both with and without radiocontrast.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The history of X-ray computed tomography goes back to at least 1917 with the mathematical theory of the Radon transform.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Oldendorf received a U.S. patent for a "radiant energy apparatus for investigating selected areas of interior objects obscured by dense material".
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The first commercially viable CT scanner was invented by Godfrey Hounsfield in 1967-1972.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] It is often claimed that revenues from the sales of The Beatles' records in the 1960s helped fund the development of the first CT scanner at EMI.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The first production X-ray CT machines were in fact called EMI scanners.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The word *tomography* is derived from the Greek *tome* 'slice' and *graphein* 'to write'.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] Computed tomography was originally known as the "EMI scan" as it was developed in the early 1970s at a research branch of EMI, a company best known today for its music and recording business.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] It was later known as *computed axial tomography* (*CAT* or *CT scan*) and *body section röntgenography*.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The term *CAT scan* is no longer in technical use because current CT scans enable for multiplanar reconstructions.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] This makes *CT scan* the most appropriate term, which is used by radiologists in common vernacular as well as in textbooks and scientific papers.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] In Medical Subject Headings (MeSH), *computed axial tomography* was used from 1977 to 1979, but the current indexing explicitly includes *X-ray* in the title.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p01] The term *sinogram* was introduced by Paul Edholm and Bertil Jacobson in 1975.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] In response to increased concern by the public and the ongoing progress of best practices, the Alliance for Radiation Safety in Pediatric Imaging was formed within the Society for Pediatric Radiology.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] This initiative has been endorsed and applied by a growing list of various professional medical organizations around the world and has received support and assistance from companies that manufacture equipment used in Radiology.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] The World Health Organization and International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) of the United Nations have also been working in this area and have ongoing projects designed to broaden best practices and lower patient radiation dose.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] An estimated 72 million scans were performed in the United States in 2007, accounting for close to half of the total per-capita dose rate from radiologic and nuclear medicine procedures.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] Of the CT scans, six to eleven percent are done in children, an increase of seven to eightfold from 1980.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] Similar increases have been seen in Europe and Asia.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] In Calgary, Canada, 12.1% of people who present to the emergency with an urgent complaint received a CT scan, most commonly either of the head or of the abdomen.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] The percentage who received CT, however, varied markedly by the emergency physician who saw them from 1.8% to 25%.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] In the emergency department in the United States, CT or MRI imaging is done in 15% of people who present with injuries as of 2007 (up from 6% in 1998).
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] The increased use of CT scans has been the greatest in two fields: screening of adults (screening CT of the lung in smokers, virtual colonoscopy, CT cardiac screening, and whole-body CT in asymptomatic patients) and CT imaging of children.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] Shortening of the scanning time to around 1 second, eliminating the strict need for the subject to remain still or be sedated, is one of the main reasons for the large increase in the pediatric population (especially for the diagnosis of appendicitis).
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] As of 2007, in the United States a proportion of CT scans are performed unnecessarily.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] Some estimates place this number at 30%.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] There are a number of reasons for this including: legal concerns, financial incentives, and desire by the public.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] For example, some healthy people avidly pay to receive full-body CT scans as screening.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] In that case, it is not at all clear that the benefits outweigh the risks and costs.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] Deciding whether and how to treat incidentalomas is complex, radiation exposure is not negligible, and the money for the scans involves opportunity cost.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] Photon-counting computed tomography is a CT technique currently under development.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] Typical CT scanners use energy integrating detectors; photons are measured as a voltage on a capacitor which is proportional to the X-rays detected.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] However, this technique is susceptible to noise and other factors which can affect the linearity of the voltage to X-ray intensity relationship.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] Photon counting detectors (PCDs) are still affected by noise but it does not change the measured counts of photons.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] PCDs have several potential advantages, including improving signal (and contrast) to noise ratios, reducing doses, improving spatial resolution, and through use of several energies, distinguishing multiple contrast agents.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] PCDs have only recently become feasible in CT scanners due to improvements in detector technologies that can cope with the volume and rate of data required.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] As of February 2016, photon counting CT is in use at six or seven sites.
[src:ct-imaging/ct-scan-p02] Some early research has found the dose reduction potential of photon counting CT for breast imaging to be very promising.
[src:ct-imaging/hounsfield-scale] The **Hounsfield scale** (/ˈhaʊnzfiːld/ *HOWNZ-feeld*), named after Sir Godfrey Hounsfield, is a quantitative scale for describing radiodensity.
[src:ct-imaging/hounsfield-scale] It is frequently used in CT scans, where its value is also termed **CT number**.
[src:ct-imaging/hounsfield-scale] where $\mu _{\textrm {water}}$ and $\mu _{\textrm {air}}$ are respectively the linear attenuation coefficients of water and air.
[src:ct-imaging/hounsfield-scale] Thus, a change of one Hounsfield unit (HU) represents a change of 0.1% of the attenuation coefficient of water since the attenuation coefficient of air is nearly zero.
[src:ct-imaging/hounsfield-scale] Calibration tests of HU with reference to water and other materials may be done to ensure standardised response.
[src:ct-imaging/hounsfield-scale] This is particularly important for CT scans used in radiotherapy treatment planning, where HU is converted to electron density.
[src:ct-imaging/hounsfield-scale] Variation in the measured values of reference materials with known composition, and variation between and within slices may be used as part of test procedures.
[src:ct-imaging/hounsfield-scale] The above standards were chosen originally to encode the radiodensity of organic tissues relative to water for 12-bit processing on clinical CT scanners.
[src:ct-imaging/hounsfield-scale] A 12-bit encoding corresponds to 4096 ( $2^{12}$ ) values, where the range (–1024 to 3071) encompasses HU values for air, soft tissue and bone.
[src:ct-imaging/hounsfield-scale] HU-based differentiation of material applies to medical-grade dual-energy CT scans but not to cone beam computed tomography (CBCT) scans, as CBCT scans provide unreliable HU readings.
[src:ct-imaging/hounsfield-scale] Values reported here are **approximations**.
[src:ct-imaging/hounsfield-scale] Different dynamics are reported from one study to another.
[src:ct-imaging/hounsfield-scale] Exact HU dynamics can vary from one CT acquisition to another due to CT acquisition and reconstruction parameters (kV, filters, reconstruction algorithms, etc.).
[src:ct-imaging/hounsfield-scale] The use of contrast agents modifies HU as well in some body parts (mainly blood).
[src:ct-imaging/hounsfield-scale] A practical application of this is in evaluation of tumors, where, for example, an adrenal tumor with a radiodensity of less than 10 HU is rather fatty in composition and almost certainly a benign adrenal adenoma.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] The reconstruction of an image from the acquired data is an inverse problem.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] Often, it is not possible to exactly solve the inverse problem directly.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] In this case, a direct algorithm has to approximate the solution, which might cause visible reconstruction artifacts in the image.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] Iterative algorithms approach the correct solution using multiple iteration steps, which allows to obtain a better reconstruction at the cost of a higher computation time.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] There are a large variety of algorithms, but each starts with an assumed image, computes projections from the image, compares the original projection data and updates the image based upon the difference between the calculated and the actual projections.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] The Algebraic Reconstruction Technique (ART) was the first iterative reconstruction technique used for computed tomography by Hounsfield.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] The iterative sparse asymptotic minimum variance algorithm is an iterative, parameter-free superresolution tomographic reconstruction method inspired by compressed sensing, with applications in synthetic-aperture radar, computed tomography scan, and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI).
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] There are typically five components to statistical iterative image reconstruction algorithms, e.g.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] A system model that relates the unknown object to the "ideal" measurements that would be recorded in the absence of measurement noise.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] Often this is a linear model of the form $\mathbf {A} x+\epsilon$ , where $\epsilon$ represents the noise.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] A statistical model that describes how the noisy measurements vary around their ideal values.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] Often Gaussian noise or Poisson statistics are assumed.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] Because Poisson statistics are closer to reality, it is more widely used.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] A cost function that is to be minimized to estimate the image coefficient vector.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] Often this cost function includes some form of regularization.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] Sometimes the regularization is based on Markov random fields.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] An algorithm, usually iterative, for minimizing the cost function, including some initial estimate of the image and some stopping criterion for terminating the iterations.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] In learned iterative reconstruction, the updating algorithm is learned from training data using techniques from machine learning such as convolutional neural networks, while still incorporating the image formation model.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] This typically gives faster and higher quality reconstructions and has been applied to CT and MRI reconstruction.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] The advantages of the iterative approach include improved insensitivity to noise and capability of reconstructing an optimal image in the case of incomplete data.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] The method has been applied in emission tomography modalities like SPECT and PET, where there is significant attenuation along ray paths and noise statistics are relatively poor.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] As another example, it is considered superior when one does not have a large set of projections available, when the projections are not distributed uniformly in angle, or when the projections are sparse or missing at certain orientations.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] These scenarios may occur in intraoperative CT, in cardiac CT, or when metal artifacts require the exclusion of some portions of the projection data.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] For example, with iterative algorithms it is possible to reconstruct images from data acquired in a very short time as required for real-time MRI (rt-MRI).
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] In Cryo Electron Tomography, where the limited number of projections are acquired due to the hardware limitations and to avoid the biological specimen damage, it can be used along with compressive sensing techniques or regularization functions (e.g.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] Huber function) to improve the reconstruction for better interpretation.
[src:ct-imaging/iterative-reconstruction] Here is an example that illustrates the benefits of iterative image reconstruction for cardiac MRI.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] A visual representation of the raw data obtained is called a *sinogram*, yet it is not sufficient for interpretation.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] In terms of mathematics, the raw data acquired by the scanner consists of multiple "projections" of the object being scanned.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] These projections are effectively the Radon transformation of the structure of the object.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Reconstruction essentially involves solving the inverse Radon transformation.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] In conventional CT machines, an X-ray tube and detector are physically rotated behind a circular shroud (see the image above right).
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Systems with a very large number of detector rows, such that the *z*-axis coverage is comparable to the *xy*-axis coverage are often termed *cone beam CT*, due to the shape of the X-ray beam (strictly, the beam is pyramidal in shape, rather than conical).
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Contrast mediums used for X-ray CT, as well as for plain film X-ray, are called radiocontrasts.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Radiocontrasts for X-ray CT are, in general, iodine-based.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] In this section, the schematic configuration and motion of the parallel beam irradiation optical system configured to obtain the p(s,θ) of above-mentioned (eq.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] In this section, how to obtain the p(s,θ) of (eq.5) by utilizing parallel beam irradiation optical system will also be explained.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Configuration and motions of parallel beam irradiation optical system, referring Fig.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Two datum coordinate systems *xy* and *ts* are imagined in order to explain the positional relations and movements of features (0)–(7) in the figure.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The *xy* and *ts* coordinate systems share the origin (6) and they are positioned on the same plane.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] That is, the *xy* plane and the *ts* plane are the same plane.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Henceforth, this virtual plane will be called "the datum plane".
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] In addition, a virtual circle centered at the abovementioned origin (6) is set on the datum plane (it will be called "the datum circle" henceforth).
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] This datum circle (5) will be represents the orbit of the parallel beam irradiation optical system.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Naturally, the origin (6), the datum circle (5), and the datum coordinate systems are virtual features which are imagined for mathematical purposes.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The μ(x,y) is absorption coefficient of the object (3) at each (x,y), p(s,θ) (7) is the collection of fluoroscopic images.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The parallel beam irradiation optical system is the key component of a CT scanner.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] It consists of a parallel beam X-ray source (2) and the screen (3).
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] They are positioned so that they face each other in parallel with the origin (6) in between, both being in contact with the datum circle (6).
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] These two features ((2) and (3)) can rotate counterclockwise around the origin (6) together with the *ts* coordinate system while maintaining the relative positional relations between themselves and with the *ts* coordinate system (so, these two features ((2) and (3)) are always opposed each other).
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The*ts* plane is positioned so that the direction from a collimated X-ray source (2) to the screen (3) matches the positive direction of the t-axis while the s-axis parallels these two features.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Henceforth, the angle between the x- and the s-axes will be indicated as θ.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] That is, parallel beam irradiation optical system where the angle between the object and the transmission beam equals θ.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] This datum circle (6) will be represents the orbit of the parallel beam irradiation optical system.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] On the other hand, the object (1) will be scanned by CT scanner is fixed to *xy* coordination system.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Hence, object (1) will not be moved while the parallel beam irradiation optical system are rotated around the object (1).
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The object (1) must be smaller than datum circle.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The distance the table moves for every 360° rotation of the X-ray generator is called the *increment* or *table feed* for axial scan modes.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] For helical scan modes, it is called *table speed*.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Setting an increment that is smaller than the slice thickness results in overlap between the slices.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] A beneficial effect of this is a smoother transition between images when scrolling through the stack.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] During the above-mentioned motion (that is pivoting around the object(1)) of parallel beam irradiation optical system, the collimated X-ray source (2) emits transmission beam (4) which are effectively "parallel rays" in a geometrical optical sense.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The traveling direction of each ray of the transmission beam (4) is parallel to the t-axis.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The transmission beam (4), emitted by the X-ray source (2), penetrates the object and reaches the screen (3) after attenuation due to absorption by the object.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Optical transmission can be presumed to occur ideally.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] That is, transmission beam penetrates without diffraction, diffusion, or reflection although it is absorbed by the object and its attenuation is assumed to occur in accordance with the Beer-Lambert law.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Consequently, a fluoroscopic image (7) is recorded on the screen as a one-dimensional image (one image is recorded for every θ corresponding to all s values).
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] When the angle between the object and transmission beam is θ and if the intensity of transmission beam (4) having reached each "s" point on the screen is expressed as p(s, θ), it expresses a fluoroscopic image (7) corresponding to each θ.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The technique of filtered back projection is one of the most established algorithmic techniques for this problem.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] It is conceptually simple, tunable and deterministic.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] It is also computationally undemanding, with modern scanners requiring only a few milliseconds per image.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] However, this is not the only technique available: the original EMI scanner solved the tomographic reconstruction problem by linear algebra, but this approach was limited by its high computational complexity, especially given the computer technology available at the time.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] More recently, manufacturers have developed iterative physical model-based maximum likelihood expectation maximization techniques.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] These techniques are advantageous because they use an internal model of the scanner's physical properties and of the physical laws of X-ray interactions.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Earlier methods, such as filtered back projection, assume a perfect scanner and highly simplified physics, which leads to a number of artifacts, high noise and impaired image resolution.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Iterative techniques provide images with improved resolution, reduced noise and fewer artifacts, as well as the ability to greatly reduce the radiation dose in certain circumstances.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The disadvantage is a very high computational requirement, but advances in computer technology and high-performance computing techniques, such as use of highly parallel GPU algorithms or use of specialized hardware such as FPGAs or ASICs, now allow practical use.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] In this section, the basic principle of tomography in the case that especially uses tomography utilizing the parallel beam irradiation optical system will be explained.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Tomography is a technology that uses a tomographic optical system to obtain virtual 'slices' (a tomographic image) of specific cross section of a scanned object, allowing the user to see inside the object without cutting.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] There are several types of tomographic optical system including the parallel beam irradiation optical system.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Parallel beam irradiation optical system may be the easiest and most practical example of a tomographic optical system therefore, in this article, explanation of "How to obtain the Tomographic image" will be based on "the parallel beam irradiation optical system".
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The resolution in tomography is typically described by the Crowther criterion.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] 3 is intended to illustrate the mathematical model and to illustrate the principle of tomography.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] In Fig.3, absorption coefficient at a cross-sectional coordinate (x, y) of the subject is modeled as μ(x, y).
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Consideration based on the above assumptions may clarify the following items.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Consider the mathematical model where the absorption coefficient of the object at each point $(x,y)$ is represented by the function $\mu (x,y)$ and suppose that the transmission beam penetrates without diffraction, diffusion, or reflection.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Also assume the beam is absorbed by the object and its attenuation occurs in accordance with the Beer-Lambert law.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] What we want to know then is the values of the function $\mu$ .
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] What we can measure will be the values of the function $p(s,\theta )$ .
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] When the attenuation conforms to the Beer-Lambert law, the relation between ${I}_{0}$ and I is given by equation (**1**) and the absorbance $p_{l}$ along the light beam path $l(t)$ is given by equation (**2**).
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Here ${I}_{0}$ is the intensity of the light beam before transmission, while I is the beam intensity after transmission.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Here, the direction from the light source toward the screen is defined as the t direction and that perpendicular to the t direction and parallel with the screen is defined as the s direction.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] By using a parallel beam irradiation optical system, one can experimentally obtain the series of fluoroscopic images (these are one-dimensional images $p_{\theta }(s)$ of a specific cross section of a scanned object) for each angle $\theta$ between the object and the transmitted light beam.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] In Fig.3, the $(x,y)$ plane rotates counter clockwise. around the point of origin in the plane in such a way "to keep mutual positional relationship between the light source (2) and screen (7) passing through the trajectory (5)." Rotation angle of this case is same as above-mentioned θ.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The beam having an angle $\theta$ is the collection of lines ${l}_{\theta ,s}(t)$ , represented by equation (**3**) below.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The function $p_{\theta }(s)$ is defined by equation (**4**).
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] This means that, $p(s,\theta )$ of following (eq.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] 5) is a resultant of Radon transformation of μ(x,y).
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] One can define following function of two variables (**5**).
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] In this article, $p(s,\theta )$ is the collection of **fluoroscopic images**.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] "What we want to know (μ(x,y))" can be reconstructed from "What we measured ( p(s,θ))" by using inverse radon transformation .
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] In the above-mentioned descriptions, "What we measured" is p(s,θ) .
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] On the other hand, "What we want to know " is μ(x,y).
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] So, the next will be "How to reconstruct μ(x,y) from p(s,θ)".
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Willi Kalender is credited with invention of the technique, and uses the term spiral CT.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Kalender argues that the terms spiral and helical are synonymous and equally acceptable.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] There are a class of image artifacts specific to helical acquisition.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Since its invention by Kalender in the 1980s, helical scan CT machines have steadily increased the number of rows of detectors (slices) they deploy.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The prototype 16 multi-slice scanner was introduced in 2001 and in 2004, 64 multislice scanners are on the market.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] These can produce an image in less than a second and thus can obtain images of the heart and its blood vessels (coronary vessels) as if frozen in time.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] In order to illuminate multiple rows of detector elements in a multi-slice scanner, the x-ray source must emit a beam which is divergent along the axial direction (i.e. a cone beam instead of a fan beam).
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] A helical CT beam trajectory is characterized by its pitch, which is equal to the table feed distance along the scan range over one gantry rotation divided by the section collimation.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] When pitch is greater than 1, the radiation dose for a given axial *field of view* (FOV) is decreased compared to conventional CT.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] At high pitches there is, however, a trade-off in terms of noise and longitudinal resolution.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] In cone-beam computed tomography (commonly abbreviated *CBCT*), the X-ray beam is conical.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] In practical helical cone beam X-ray CT machines, the source and array of detectors are mounted on a rotating gantry while the patient is moved axially at a uniform rate.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Earlier X-ray CT scanners imaged one slice at a time by rotating source and one-dimensional array of detectors while the patient remained static.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The helical scan method reduces the X-ray dose to the patient required for a given resolution while scanning more quickly.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] This is, however, at the cost of greater mathematical complexity in the reconstruction of the image from the measurements.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] The earliest sensors were scintillation detectors, with photomultiplier tubes excited by (typically) cesium iodide crystals.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Cesium iodide was replaced during the 1980s by ion chambers containing high-pressure xenon gas.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] These systems were in turn replaced by scintillation systems based on photodiodes instead of photomultipliers and modern scintillation materials (for example rare-earth garnet or rare-earth oxide ceramics) with more desirable characteristics.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Initial machines would rotate the X-ray source and detectors around a stationary object.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Following a complete rotation, the object would be moved along its axis, and the next rotation started.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] Newer machines permitted continuous rotation with the object to be imaged slowly and smoothly slid through the X-ray ring.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] These are called *helical* or *spiral CT* machines.
[src:ct-imaging/operation-of-computed-tomography] A subsequent development of helical CT was multi-slice (or multi-detector) CT; instead of a single row of detectors, multiple rows of detectors are used effectively capturing multiple cross-sections simultaneously.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] In mathematics, the **Radon transform** is the integral transform which takes a function *f* defined on the plane to a function *Rf* defined on the (two-dimensional) space of lines in the plane, whose value at a particular line is equal to the line integral of the function over that line.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] The transform was introduced in 1917 by Johann Radon, who also provided a formula for the inverse transform.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] Radon further included formulas for the transform in three dimensions, in which the integral is taken over planes (integrating over lines is known as the X-ray transform).
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] It was later generalized to higher-dimensional Euclidean spaces and more broadly in the context of integral geometry.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] The complex analogue of the Radon transform is known as the Penrose transform.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] The Radon transform is widely applicable to tomography, the creation of an image from the projection data associated with cross-sectional scans of an object.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] If a function f represents an unknown density, then the Radon transform represents the projection data obtained as the output of a tomographic scan.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] The inverse of the Radon transform can be used to reconstruct the original density from the projection data, and thus it forms the mathematical underpinning for tomographic reconstruction, also known as iterative reconstruction.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] The Radon transform data is often called a **sinogram** because the Radon transform of an off-center point source is a sinusoid.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] Consequently, the Radon transform of a number of small objects appears graphically as a number of blurred sine waves with different amplitudes and phases.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] The Radon transform is useful in computed axial tomography (CAT scan), barcode scanners, electron microscopy of macromolecular assemblies like viruses and protein complexes, reflection seismology and in the solution of hyperbolic partial differential equations.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] $Rf(\xi )=\int _{\xi }f(\mathbf {x} )\,d\sigma (\mathbf {x} ),\quad \forall \xi \in \Sigma _{n}$ where the integral is taken with respect to the natural hypersurface measure, $d\sigma$ (generalizing the $\vert d\mathbf {x} \vert$ term from the 2 -dimensional case).
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] Observe that any element of $\Sigma _{n}$ is characterized as the solution locus of an equation $\mathbf {x} \cdot \alpha =s$ , where $\alpha \in S^{n-1}$ is a unit vector and $s\in \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] The X-ray transform is the most widely used special case of this construction, and is obtained by integrating over straight lines.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] The Radon transform is closely related to the Fourier transform.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] Thus the two-dimensional Fourier transform of the initial function along a line at the inclination angle $\alpha$ is the one variable Fourier transform of the Radon transform (acquired at angle $\alpha$ ) of that function.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] This fact can be used to compute both the Radon transform and its inverse.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] The image of the Radon transform on $S^{n-1}\times \mathbb {R}$ can be characterized for functions of sufficient regularity and decay.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] There are also conditions on the moments of the Radon transform.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] is the restriction to $S^{n-1}$ of a homogeneous polynomial in $\alpha$ of degree k .
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] which is a homogeneous polynomial in $\alpha$ .
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] Conversely, the Helgason–Ludwig range theorem states that these conditions characterize the range of the Radon transform on appropriate test-function spaces.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] For example, a smooth rapidly decreasing function g on $S^{n-1}\times \mathbb {R}$ is the Radon transform of a Schwartz function on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ if and only if it satisfies the symmetry condition and the above moment conditions.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] A corresponding compactly supported version characterizes the image of $C_{c}^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ ; in that case one also has the support relation that if f is supported in the ball $|x|\leq A$ , then $Rf(\alpha ,s)=0$ for $|s|>A$ .
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] In tomography, these consistency conditions describe when projection data can arise from an actual object rather than from an arbitrary function of angle and displacement.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] The dual Radon transform is a kind of adjoint to the Radon transform.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] Let $\Delta$ denote the Laplacian on $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ defined by: $\Delta ={\frac {\partial ^{2}}{\partial x_{1}^{2}}}+\cdots +{\frac {\partial ^{2}}{\partial x_{n}^{2}}}$ This is a natural rotationally invariant second-order differential operator.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] On $\Sigma _{n}$ , the "radial" second derivative $Lf(\alpha ,s)\equiv {\frac {\partial ^{2}}{\partial s^{2}}}f(\alpha ,s)$ is also rotationally invariant.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] In imaging and numerical analysis this is exploited to reduce multi-dimensional problems into single-dimensional ones, as a dimensional splitting method.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] The process of *reconstruction* produces the image (or function f in the previous section) from its projection data.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] The convolution kernel h is referred to as Ramp filter in some literature.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] Intuitively, in the *filtered back-projection* formula, by analogy with differentiation, for which ${\textstyle \left({\widehat {{\frac {d}{dx}}f}}\right)\!(k)=ik{\widehat {f}}(k)}$ , we see that the filter performs an operation similar to a derivative.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] Roughly speaking, then, the filter makes objects *more* singular.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] A quantitive statement of the ill-posedness of Radon inversion goes as follows: ${\widehat {{\mathcal {R}}^{*}{\mathcal {R}}[g]}}(\mathbf {k} )={\frac {1}{\|\mathbf {k} \|}}{\hat {g}}(\mathbf {k} )$ where ${\mathcal {R}}^{*}$ is the previously defined adjoint to the Radon transform.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] Since these singular values tend to 0 , ${\mathcal {R}}^{-1}$ is unbounded.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] Compared with the *Filtered Back-projection* method, iterative reconstruction costs large computation time, limiting its practical use.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] However, due to the ill-posedness of Radon Inversion, the *Filtered Back-projection* method may be infeasible in the presence of discontinuity or noise.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] Iterative reconstruction methods (*e.g.* iterative Sparse Asymptotic Minimum Variance) could provide metal artefact reduction, noise and dose reduction for the reconstructed result that attract much research interest around the world.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] Explicit and computationally efficient inversion formulas for the Radon transform and its dual are available.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] In two dimensions, the operator ${\mathcal {H}}_{s}{\frac {d}{ds}}$ appears in image processing as a ramp filter.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] As the filtering step can be performed efficiently (for example using digital signal processing techniques) and the back projection step is simply an accumulation of values in the pixels of the image, this results in a highly efficient, and hence widely used, algorithm.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] In algebraic geometry, a Radon transform (also known as the *Brylinski–Radon transform*) is constructed as follows.
[src:ct-imaging/radon-transform] The main theorem about this transform is that this transform induces an equivalence of the categories of perverse sheaves on the projective space and its dual projective space, up to constant sheaves.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] An **X-ray** is a form of high-energy electromagnetic radiation with a wavelength shorter than those of ultraviolet rays and longer than those of gamma rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Roughly, X-rays have a wavelength ranging from 10 nanometers to 10 picometers, corresponding to frequencies in the range of 30 petahertz to 30 exahertz (3×1016 Hz to 3×1019 Hz) and photon energies in the range of 100 eV to 100 keV, respectively.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] X-rays were discovered in 1895 by the German scientist Wilhelm Conrad Röntgen, who named it *X-radiation* to signify an unknown type of radiation.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] However X-rays are ionizing radiation and exposure can be hazardous to health, causing DNA damage, cancer and, at higher intensities, burns and radiation sickness.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Their generation and use is strictly controlled by public health authorities.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] X-rays were originally noticed in science as a type of unidentified radiation emanating from discharge tubes by experimenters investigating cathode rays produced by such tubes, which are energetic electron beams that were first observed in 1869.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Early researchers noticed effects that were attributable to them in many of the early Crookes tubes (invented around 1875).
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Crookes tubes created free electrons by ionization of the residual air in the tube by a high DC voltage of anywhere between a few kilovolts and 100 kV.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This voltage accelerated the electrons coming from the cathode to a high enough velocity that they created X-rays when they struck the anode or the glass wall of the tube.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The earliest experimenter thought to have (unknowingly) produced X-rays was William Morgan.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In 1785, he presented a paper to the Royal Society of London describing the effects of passing electrical currents through a partially evacuated glass tube, producing a glow created by X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This work was further explored by Humphry Davy and his assistant Michael Faraday.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Starting in 1888, Philipp Lenard conducted experiments to see whether cathode rays could pass out of the Crookes tube into the air.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] He built a Crookes tube with a "window" at the end made of thin aluminium, facing the cathode so the cathode rays would strike it (later called a "Lenard tube").
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] He found that something came through, that would expose photographic plates and cause fluorescence.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] He measured the penetrating power of these rays through various materials.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] It has been suggested that at least some of these "Lenard rays" were actually X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Hermann von Helmholtz formulated mathematical equations for X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] He postulated a dispersion theory before Röntgen made his discovery and announcement.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] He based it on the electromagnetic theory of light.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] However, he did not work with actual X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In early 1890 photographer William Jennings and associate professor of the University of Pennsylvania Arthur W.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Goodspeed were making photographs of coins with electric sparks.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] On 22 February after the end of their experiments two coins were left on a stack of photographic plates before Goodspeed demonstrated to Jennings the operation of Crookes tubes.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] While developing the plates, Jennings noticed disks of unknown origin on some of the plates, but nobody could explain them, and they moved on.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Only in 1896 they realized that they accidentally made an X-ray photograph (they didn't claim a discovery).
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Also in 1890, Röntgen's assistant Ludwig Zehnder noticed a flash of light from a fluorescent screen immediately before the covered tube he was switching on punctured.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] When Stanford University physics professor Fernando Sanford conducted his "electric photography" experiments in 1891–1893 by photographing coins in the light of electric sparks, like Jennings and Goodspeed, he may have unknowingly generated and detected X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] His letter of 6 January 1893 to the *Physical Review* was duly published and an article entitled *Without Lens or Light, Photographs Taken With Plate and Object in Darkness* appeared in the *San Francisco Examiner*.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In 1894, Nikola Tesla noticed damaged film in his lab that seemed to be associated with Crookes tube experiments and began investigating this invisible, radiant energy.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] After Röntgen identified the X-ray, Tesla began making X-ray images of his own using high voltages and tubes of his own design, as well as Crookes tubes.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] On November 8th, 1895, German physics professor Wilhelm Röntgen discovered X-rays while experimenting with Lenard tubes and Crookes tubes and began studying them.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] He wrote an initial report "On a new kind of ray: A preliminary communication" and on 28 December 1895, submitted it to Würzburg's Physical-Medical Society journal.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This was the first paper written on X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Röntgen referred to the radiation as "X", to indicate that it was an unknown type of radiation.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Some early texts refer to them as Chi-rays, having interpreted "X" as the uppercase Greek letter Chi, *Χ*.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] He noticed a faint green glow from the screen, about 1 meter (3.3 ft) away.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Röntgen realized some invisible rays coming from the tube were passing through the cardboard to make the screen glow.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] He found they could also pass through books and papers on his desk.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Röntgen threw himself into investigating these unknown rays systematically.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Two months after his initial discovery, he published his paper.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Röntgen discovered their medical use when he made a picture of his wife's hand on a photographic plate formed due to X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The photograph of his wife's hand was the first photograph of a human body part using X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The discovery of X-rays generated significant interest.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Röntgen's biographer Otto Glasser estimated that, in 1896 alone, as many as 49 essays and 1044 articles about the new rays were published.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This was probably a conservative estimate, if one considers that nearly every paper around the world extensively reported about the new discovery, with a magazine such as *Science* dedicating as many as 23 articles to it in that year alone.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Sensationalist reactions to the new discovery included publications linking the new kind of rays to occult and paranormal theories, such as telepathy.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The name X-rays stuck, although (over Röntgen's great objections) many of his colleagues suggested calling them *Röntgen rays*.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] They are still referred to as such in many languages, including German, Hungarian, Ukrainian, Danish, Polish, Czech, Bulgarian, Swedish, Finnish, Portuguese, Estonian, Slovak, Slovenian, Turkish, Russian, Latvian, Lithuanian, Albanian, Japanese, Dutch, Georgian, Hebrew, Icelandic, and Norwegian.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Röntgen received the inaugural Nobel Prize in Physics for his discovery.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Röntgen immediately noticed X-rays could have medical applications.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Along with his 28 December Physical-Medical Society submission, he sent a letter to physicians he knew around Europe (1 January 1896).
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] News (and the creation of "shadowgrams") spread rapidly with Scottish electrical engineer Alan Archibald Campbell-Swinton being the first after Röntgen to create an X-ray photograph (of a hand).
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Through February, there were 46 experimenters taking up the technique in North America alone.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The first use of X-rays under clinical conditions was by John Hall-Edwards in Birmingham, England on 11 January 1896, when he radiographed a needle stuck in the hand of an associate.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] On 14 February 1896, Hall-Edwards was also the first to use X-rays in a surgical operation.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In early 1896, several weeks after Röntgen's discovery, Ivan Romanovich Tarkhanov irradiated frogs and insects with X-rays, concluding that the rays "not only photograph, but also affect the living function".
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] At around the same time, the zoological illustrator James Green began to use X-rays to examine fragile specimens.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] George Albert Boulenger first mentioned this work in a paper he delivered before the Zoological Society of London in May 1896.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The book *Sciagraphs of British Batrachians and Reptiles* (sciagraph is an obsolete name for an X-ray photograph), by Green and James H.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Gardiner, with a foreword by Boulenger, was published in 1897.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The first medical X-ray made in the United States was obtained using a discharge tube of Ivan Puluj's design.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In January 1896, on reading of Röntgen's discovery, Frank Austin of Dartmouth College tested all of the discharge tubes in the physics laboratory and found that only the Puluj tube produced X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This was a result of Puluj's inclusion of an oblique "target" of mica, used for holding samples of fluorescent material, within the tube.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Many experimenters, including Röntgen himself in his original experiments, came up with methods to view X-ray images "live" using some form of luminescent screen.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Röntgen used a screen coated with barium platinocyanide.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] On 5 February 1896, live imaging devices were developed by both Italian scientist Enrico Salvioni (his "cryptoscope") and William Francis Magie of Princeton University (his "Skiascope"), both using barium platinocyanide.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] American inventor Thomas Edison started research soon after Röntgen's discovery and investigated materials' ability to fluoresce when exposed to X-rays, finding that calcium tungstate was the most effective substance.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In May 1896, he developed the first mass-produced live imaging device, his "Vitascope", later called the fluoroscope, which became the standard for medical X-ray examinations.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Edison dropped X-ray research around 1903, before the death of Clarence Madison Dally, one of his glassblowers.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Dally had a habit of testing X-ray tubes on his own hands, developing a cancer in them so tenacious that both arms were amputated in a futile attempt to save his life; in 1904, he became the first known death attributed to X-ray exposure.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] During the time the fluoroscope was being developed, Serbian American physicist Mihajlo Pupin, using a calcium tungstate screen developed by Edison, found that using a fluorescent screen decreased the exposure time it took to create an X-ray for medical imaging from an hour to a few minutes.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] President William McKinley was shot twice in an assassination attempt while attending the Pan American Exposition in Buffalo, New York.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] While one bullet only grazed his sternum, another had lodged somewhere deep inside his abdomen and could not be found.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] A worried McKinley aide sent word to inventor Thomas Edison to rush an X-ray machine to Buffalo to find the stray bullet.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] While the shooting itself had not been lethal, gangrene had developed along the path of the bullet, and McKinley died of septic shock due to bacterial infection six days later.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] With the widespread experimentation with X‑rays after their discovery in 1895 by scientists, physicians, and inventors came many stories of burns, hair loss, and worse in technical journals of the time.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In February 1896, Professor John Daniel and William Lofland Dudley of Vanderbilt University reported hair loss after Dudley was X-rayed.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] A child who had been shot in the head was brought to the Vanderbilt laboratory in 1896.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Before trying to find the bullet, an experiment was attempted, for which Dudley "with his characteristic devotion to science" volunteered.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Hawks, a graduate of Columbia College, suffered severe hand and chest burns from an X-ray demonstration.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] It was reported in *Electrical Review* and led to many other reports of problems associated with X-rays being sent in to the publication.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Many experimenters including Elihu Thomson at Edison's lab, William J.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Morton, and Nikola Tesla also reported burns.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Elihu Thomson deliberately exposed a finger to an X-ray tube over a period of time and suffered pain, swelling, and blistering.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Other effects were sometimes blamed for the damage including ultraviolet rays and (according to Tesla) ozone.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Many physicians claimed there were no effects from X-ray exposure at all.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] On 3 August 1905, in San Francisco, California, Elizabeth Fleischman, an American X-ray pioneer, died from complications as a result of her work with X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Hall-Edwards developed a cancer (then called X-ray dermatitis) sufficiently advanced by 1904 to cause him to write papers and give public addresses on the dangers of X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] His left arm had to be amputated at the elbow in 1908, and four fingers on his right arm soon thereafter, leaving only a thumb.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] His amputated left hand was placed at Birmingham University as a specimen.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The many applications of X-rays immediately generated enormous interest.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Workshops began making specialized versions of Crookes tubes for generating X-rays and these first-generation cold cathode or Crookes X-ray tubes were used until about 1920.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] A typical early 20th-century medical X-ray system consisted of a Ruhmkorff coil connected to a cold cathode Crookes X-ray tube.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] A spark gap was typically connected to the high voltage side in parallel to the tube and used for diagnostic purposes.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The spark gap allowed detecting the polarity of the sparks, measuring voltage by the length of the sparks thus determining the "hardness" of the vacuum of the tube, and it provided a load in the event the X-ray tube was disconnected.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] To detect the hardness of the tube, the spark gap was initially opened to the widest setting.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] While the coil was operating, the operator reduced the gap until sparks began to appear.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] A tube in which the spark gap began to spark at around 6.4 centimeters (2.5 in) was considered soft (low vacuum) and suitable for thin body parts such as hands and arms.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] A 13-centimeter (5 in) spark indicated the tube was suitable for shoulders and knees.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] An 18-to-23-centimeter (7 to 9 in) spark would indicate a higher vacuum suitable for imaging the abdomen of larger individuals.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Since the spark gap was connected in parallel to the tube, the spark gap had to be opened until the sparking ceased to operate the tube for imaging.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Exposure time for photographic plates was around half a minute for a hand to a couple of minutes for a thorax.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The plates may have a small addition of fluorescent salt to reduce exposure times.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] They had to contain a small quantity of gas (invariably air) as a current will not flow in such a tube if they are fully evacuated.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] However, as time passed, the X-rays caused the glass to absorb the gas, causing the tube to generate "harder" X-rays until it soon stopped operating.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Larger and more frequently used tubes were provided with devices for restoring the air, known as "softeners".
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] These often took the form of a small side tube that contained a small piece of mica, a mineral that traps relatively large quantities of air within its structure.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] A small electrical heater heated the mica, causing it to release a small amount of air, thus restoring the tube's efficiency.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] However, the mica had a limited life, and the restoration process was difficult to control.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In 1904, John Ambrose Fleming invented the thermionic diode, the first kind of vacuum tube.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This used a hot cathode that caused an electric current to flow in a vacuum.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This idea was quickly applied to X-ray tubes, and hence heated-cathode X-ray tubes, called "Coolidge tubes", completely replaced the troublesome cold cathode tubes by about 1920.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In about 1906, the physicist Charles Barkla discovered that X-rays could be scattered by gases, and that each element had a characteristic X-ray spectrum.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] He won the 1917 Nobel Prize in Physics for this discovery.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In 1912, Max von Laue, Paul Knipping, and Walter Friedrich first observed the diffraction of X-rays by crystals.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This discovery, along with the early work of Paul Peter Ewald, William Henry Bragg, and William Lawrence Bragg, gave birth to the field of X-ray crystallography.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In 1913, Henry Moseley performed crystallography experiments with X-rays emanating from various metals and formulated Moseley's law which relates the frequency of the X-rays to the atomic number of the metal.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The Coolidge X-ray tube was invented the same year by William D.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] It made possible the continuous emissions of X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Modern X-ray tubes are based on this design, often employing the use of rotating targets which allow for significantly higher heat dissipation than static targets, further allowing higher quantity X-ray output for use in high-powered applications such as rotational CT scanners.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The use of X-rays for medical purposes (which developed into the field of radiation therapy) was pioneered by Major John Hall-Edwards in Birmingham, England.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Then in 1908, he had to have his left arm amputated because of the spread of X-ray dermatitis on his arm.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Medical science also used the motion picture to study human physiology.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In 1913, a motion picture was made in Detroit showing a hard-boiled egg inside a human stomach.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This early X-ray movie was recorded at a rate of one still image every four seconds.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Dr Lewis Gregory Cole of New York was a pioneer of the technique, which he called "serial radiography".
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In 1918, X-rays were used in association with motion picture cameras to capture the human skeleton in motion.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In 1920, it was used to record the movements of tongue and teeth in the study of languages by the Institute of Phonetics in England.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In 1914, Marie Curie developed radiological cars to support soldiers injured in World War I.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The cars would allow for rapid X-ray imaging of wounded soldiers so battlefield surgeons could quickly and more accurately operate.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] From the early 1920s through to the 1950s, X-ray machines were developed to assist in the fitting of shoes and were sold to commercial shoe stores.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Concerns regarding the impact of frequent or poorly controlled use were expressed in the 1950s, leading to the practice's eventual decline.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Canberra proposed a ban in 1957, while Switzerland prohibited the machines in 1989.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The X-ray microscope was developed during the late 1940s and early 1950s.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The Chandra X-ray Observatory, launched on 23 July 1999, has been allowing the exploration of the very violent processes in the universe that produce X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Unlike visible light, which gives a relatively stable view of the universe, the X-ray universe is unstable.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] It features stars being torn apart by black holes, galactic collisions, and novae, and neutron stars that build up layers of plasma that then explode into space.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] An X-ray laser device was proposed as part of the Reagan Administration's Strategic Defense Initiative in the 1980s, but the only test of the device (a sort of laser "blaster" or death ray, powered by a thermonuclear explosion) gave inconclusive results.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] For technical and political reasons, the overall project (including the X-ray laser) was defunded (though was later revived by the second Bush Administration as National Missile Defense using different technologies).
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Phase-contrast X-ray imaging refers to a variety of techniques that use phase information of an X-ray beam to form the image.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Due to its good sensitivity to density differences, it is especially useful for imaging soft tissues.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] It has become an important method for visualizing cellular and histological structures in a wide range of biological and medical studies.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] There are several technologies being used for X-ray phase-contrast imaging, all using different principles to convert phase variations in the X-rays emerging from an object into intensity variations.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] These include propagation-based phase contrast, Talbot interferometry, refraction-enhanced imaging, and X-ray interferometry.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] These methods provide higher contrast compared to normal absorption-based X-ray imaging, making it possible to distinguish from each other details that have almost similar density.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] A disadvantage is that these methods require more sophisticated equipment, such as synchrotron or microfocus X-ray sources, X-ray optics, and high resolution X-ray detectors.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] X-rays with high photon energies above 5–10 keV (below 0.2–0.1 nm wavelength) are called *hard X-rays*, while those with lower energy (and longer wavelength) are called *soft X-rays*.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The intermediate range with photon energies of several keV is often referred to as *tender X-rays*.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Due to their penetrating ability, hard X-rays are widely used to image the inside of objects (e.g. in medical radiography and airport security).
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The term *X-ray* is metonymically used to refer to a radiographic image produced using this method, in addition to the method itself.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Since the wavelengths of hard X-rays are similar to the size of atoms, they are also useful for determining crystal structures by X-ray crystallography.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] By contrast, soft X-rays are easily absorbed in air; the attenuation length of 600 eV (~2 nm) X-rays in water is less than 1 micrometer.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] There is no consensus for a definition distinguishing between X-rays and gamma rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] One common practice is to distinguish between the two types of radiation based on their source: X-rays are emitted by electron deexcitation, while gamma rays are emitted by the decay of atomic nuclei.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] For example, since there is overlap in the energy ranges of gamma and x-rays, if the origin of a photon is not known, it might not be clear what to classify the photon as.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Another practice is to distinguish X- and gamma radiation on the basis of wavelength (or, equivalently, frequency or photon energy), with radiation shorter than some arbitrary wavelength, such as 10−11 m (0.1 Å), defined as gamma radiation.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This criterion assigns a photon to an unambiguous category, but is only possible if wavelength is known.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] (Some measurement techniques do not distinguish between detected wavelengths.) However, these two definitions often coincide since the electromagnetic radiation emitted by X-ray tubes generally has a longer wavelength and lower photon energy than the radiation emitted by radioactive nuclei.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Occasionally, one term or the other is used in specific contexts due to historical precedent, based on measurement (detection) technique, or based on their intended use rather than their wavelength or source.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Thus, gamma-rays generated for medical and industrial uses, for example radiotherapy, in the ranges of 6–20 MeV, can in this context also be referred to as X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] X-ray photons carry enough energy to ionize atoms and disrupt molecular bonds.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This makes it a type of ionizing radiation, and therefore harmful to living tissue.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] A very high radiation dose over a short period of time causes burns and radiation sickness, while lower doses can give an increased risk of radiation-induced cancer.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In medical imaging, this increased cancer risk is generally greatly outweighed by the benefits of the examination.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The ionizing capability of X-rays can be used in cancer treatment to kill malignant cells using radiation therapy.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] It is also used for material characterization using X-ray spectroscopy.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Hard X-rays can traverse relatively thick objects without being much absorbed or scattered.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] For this reason, X-rays are widely used to image the inside of visually opaque objects.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The most often seen applications are in medical radiography and airport security scanners, but similar techniques are also important in industry (e.g. industrial radiography and industrial CT scanning) and research (e.g. small animal CT).
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The penetration depth varies with several orders of magnitude over the X-ray spectrum.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This allows the photon energy to be adjusted for the application so as to give sufficient transmission through the object and at the same time provide good contrast in the image.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] X-rays have much shorter wavelengths than visible light, which makes it possible to probe structures much smaller than can be seen using a normal microscope.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This property is used in X-ray microscopy to acquire high-resolution images, and also in X-ray crystallography to determine the positions of atoms in crystals.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] X-rays interact with matter in three main ways, through photoabsorption, Compton scattering, and Rayleigh scattering.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The strength of these interactions depends on the energy of the X-rays and the elemental composition of the material, but not much on chemical properties, since the X-ray photon energy is much higher than chemical binding energies.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Photoabsorption or photoelectric absorption is the dominant interaction mechanism in the soft X-ray regime and for the lower hard X-ray energies.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] At higher energies, Compton scattering dominates.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The probability of a photoelectric absorption per unit mass is approximately proportional to ${\textstyle Z^{3}/E^{3}}$ , where ${\textstyle Z}$ is the atomic number and ${\textstyle E}$ is the energy of the incident photon.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This rule is not valid close to inner shell electron binding energies where there are abrupt changes in interaction probability, so called absorption edges.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] However, the general trend of high absorption coefficients and thus short penetration depths for low photon energies and high atomic numbers is very strong.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] For soft tissue, photoabsorption dominates up to about 26 keV photon energy where Compton scattering takes over.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] For higher atomic number substances, this limit is higher.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The high amount of calcium ( ${\textstyle Z=20}$ ) in bones, together with their high density, is what makes them show up so clearly on medical radiographs.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] A photoabsorbed photon transfers all its energy to the electron with which it interacts, thus ionizing the atom to which the electron was bound and producing a photoelectron that is likely to ionize more atoms in its path.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] An outer electron will fill the vacant electron position and produce either a characteristic X-ray or an Auger electron.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] These effects can be used for elemental detection through X-ray spectroscopy or Auger electron spectroscopy.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Compton scattering is the predominant interaction between X-rays and soft tissue in medical imaging.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Compton scattering is an inelastic scattering of the X-ray photon by an outer shell electron.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Part of the energy of the photon is transferred to the scattering electron, thereby ionizing the atom and increasing the wavelength of the X-ray.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The scattered photon can go in any direction, but a direction similar to the original direction is more likely, especially for high-energy X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The probability for different scattering angles is described by the Klein–Nishina formula.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The transferred energy can be directly obtained from the scattering angle from the conservation of energy and momentum.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Rayleigh scattering is the dominant elastic scattering mechanism in the X-ray regime.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Inelastic forward scattering gives rise to the refractive index, which for X-rays is only slightly below 1.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Whenever charged particles (electrons or ions) of sufficient energy hit a material, X-rays are produced.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] X-rays can be generated by an X-ray tube, a vacuum tube that uses a high voltage to accelerate the electrons released by a hot cathode to a high velocity.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The high velocity electrons collide with a metal target, the anode, creating the X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In medical X-ray tubes the target is usually tungsten or a more crack-resistant alloy of rhenium (5%) and tungsten (95%), but sometimes molybdenum for more specialized applications, such as when softer X-rays are needed as in mammography.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In crystallography, a copper target is most common, with cobalt often being used when fluorescence from iron content in the sample might otherwise present a problem.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] When even lower energies are needed, as in X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy, the Kα X-rays from an aluminium or magnesium target are often used.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The maximum energy of the produced X-ray photon is limited by the energy of the incident electron, which is equal to the voltage on the tube times the electron charge, so an 80 kV tube cannot create X-rays with an energy greater than 80 keV.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] *Bremsstrahlung*: This is radiation given off by the electrons as they are scattered by the strong electric field near the nuclei.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] These X-rays have a continuous spectrum.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The frequency of *Bremsstrahlung* is limited by the energy of incident electrons.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] So, the resulting output of a tube consists of a continuous *Bremsstrahlung* spectrum falling off to zero at the tube voltage, plus several spikes at the characteristic lines.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The voltages used in diagnostic X-ray tubes range from roughly 20 kV to 150 kV and thus the highest energies of the X-ray photons range from roughly 20 keV to 150 keV.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Both of these X-ray production processes are inefficient, with only about one percent of the electrical energy used by the tube converted into X-rays, and thus most of the electric power consumed by the tube is released as waste heat.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] When producing a usable flux of X-rays, the X-ray tube must be designed to dissipate the excess heat.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] A specialized source of X-rays which is becoming widely used in research is synchrotron radiation, which is generated by particle accelerators.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Its unique features are X-ray outputs many orders of magnitude greater than those of X-ray tubes, wide X-ray spectra, excellent collimation, and linear polarization.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Short nanosecond bursts of X-rays peaking at 15 keV in energy may be reliably produced by peeling pressure-sensitive adhesive tape from its backing in a moderate vacuum.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This is likely to be the result of recombination of electrical charges produced by triboelectric charging.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The intensity of X-ray triboluminescence is sufficient for it to be used as a source for X-ray imaging.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] X-rays can also be produced by fast protons or other positive ions.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The proton-induced X-ray emission or particle-induced X-ray emission is widely used as an analytical procedure.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] For high energies, the production cross section is proportional to *Z*12*Z*2−4, where *Z*1 refers to the atomic number of the ion, *Z*2 refers to that of the target atom.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] An overview of these cross sections is given in the same reference.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] X-rays are also produced in lightning accompanying terrestrial gamma-ray flashes.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The underlying mechanism is the acceleration of electrons in lightning related electric fields and the subsequent production of photons through *Bremsstrahlung*.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This produces photons with energies of some few keV and several tens of MeV.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In laboratory discharges with a gap size of approximately 1 meter length and a peak voltage of 1 MV, X-rays with a characteristic energy of 160 keV are observed.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] A possible explanation is the encounter of two streamers and the production of high-energy run-away electrons; however, microscopic simulations have shown that the duration of electric field enhancement between two streamers is too short to produce a significant number of run-away electrons.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Recently, it has been proposed that air perturbations in the vicinity of streamers can facilitate the production of run-away electrons and hence of X-rays from discharges.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] X-ray detectors vary in shape and function depending on their purpose.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Imaging detectors such as those used for radiography were originally based on photographic plates and later photographic film, but are now mostly replaced by various digital detector types such as image plates and flat panel detectors.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] For radiation protection direct exposure hazard is often evaluated using ionization chambers, while dosimeters are used to measure the radiation dose the person has been exposed to.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] X-ray spectra can be measured either by energy dispersive or wavelength dispersive spectrometers.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] For X-ray diffraction applications, such as X-ray crystallography, hybrid photon counting detectors are widely used.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Since Röntgen's discovery that X-rays can identify bone structures, X-rays have been used for medical imaging.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The first medical use was less than a month after his paper on the subject.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Up to 2010, five billion medical imaging examinations had been conducted worldwide.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Radiation exposure from medical imaging in 2006 made up about 50% of total ionizing radiation exposure in the United States.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Projectional radiography is the practice of producing two-dimensional images using X-ray radiation.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Bones contain a high concentration of calcium, which, due to its relatively high atomic number, absorbs X-rays efficiently.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This reduces the amount of X-rays reaching the detector in the shadow of the bones, making them clearly visible on the radiograph.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The lungs and trapped gas also show up clearly because of lower absorption compared to tissue, while differences between tissue types are harder to see.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Projectional radiographs are useful in the detection of pathology of the skeletal system as well as for detecting some disease processes in soft tissue.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Some notable examples are the very common chest X-ray, which can be used to identify lung diseases such as pneumonia, lung cancer, or pulmonary edema, and the abdominal x-ray, which can detect bowel (or intestinal) obstruction, free air (from visceral perforations), and free fluid (in ascites).
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] X-rays may also be used to detect pathology such as gallstones (which are rarely radiopaque) or kidney stones which are often (but not always) visible.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Traditional plain X-rays are less useful in the imaging of soft tissues such as the brain or muscle.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] One area where projectional radiographs are used extensively is in evaluating how an orthopedic implant, such as a knee, hip or shoulder replacement, is situated in the body with respect to the surrounding bone.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This can be assessed in two dimensions from plain radiographs, or it can be assessed in three dimensions if a technique called '2D to 3D registration' is used.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This technique purportedly negates projection errors associated with evaluating implant position from plain radiographs.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Dental radiography is commonly used in the diagnoses of common oral problems, such as cavities.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In medical diagnostic applications, the low energy (soft) X-rays are unwanted, since they are totally absorbed by the body, increasing the radiation dose without contributing to the image.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Hence, a thin metal sheet, often of aluminium, called an X-ray filter, is usually placed over the window of the X-ray tube, absorbing the low energy part in the spectrum.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This is called *hardening* the beam since it shifts the center of the spectrum towards higher energy (or harder) X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] To generate an image of the cardiovascular system, including the arteries and veins (angiography) an initial image is taken of the anatomical region of interest.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] A second image is then taken of the same region after an iodinated contrast agent has been injected into the blood vessels within this area.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] These two images are then digitally subtracted, leaving an image of only the iodinated contrast outlining the blood vessels.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The radiologist or surgeon then compares the image obtained to normal anatomical images to determine whether there is any damage or blockage of the vessel.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Computed tomography (CT scanning) is a medical imaging modality where tomographic images or slices of specific areas of the body are obtained from a large series of two-dimensional X-ray images taken in different directions.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] These cross-sectional images can be combined into a three-dimensional image of the inside of the body.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] CT scans are a quicker and more cost effective imaging modality that can be used for diagnostic and therapeutic purposes in various medical disciplines.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Fluoroscopy is an imaging technique commonly used by physicians or radiation therapists to obtain real-time moving images of the internal structures of a patient through the use of a fluoroscope.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In its simplest form, a fluoroscope consists of an X-ray source and a fluorescent screen, between which a patient is placed.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] However, modern fluoroscopes couple the screen to an X-ray image intensifier and CCD video camera allowing the images to be recorded and played on a monitor.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This method may use a contrast material.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Examples include cardiac catheterization (to examine for coronary artery blockages), embolization procedures (to stop bleeding during hemorrhoidal artery embolization), and barium swallow (to examine for esophageal disorders and swallowing disorders).
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] As of recent, modern fluoroscopy uses short bursts of x-rays, rather than a continuous beam, to effectively lower radiation exposure for both the patient and operator.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The use of X-rays as a treatment is known as radiation therapy and is largely used for the management (including palliation) of cancer; it requires higher radiation doses than those received for imaging alone.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] X-rays beams are used for treating skin cancers using lower energy X-ray beams while higher energy beams are used for treating cancers within the body such as brain, lung, prostate, and breast.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] X-rays are a form of ionizing radiation, and are classified as a carcinogen by both the World Health Organization's International Agency for Research on Cancer and the U.S. government.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Diagnostic X-rays (primarily from CT scans due to the large dose used) increase the risk of developmental problems and cancer in those exposed.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] It is estimated that 0.4% of current cancers in the United States are due to computed tomography (CT scans) performed in the past and that this may increase to as high as 1.5–2% with 2007 rates of CT usage.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Experimental and epidemiological data currently do not support the proposition that there is a threshold dose of radiation below which there is no increased risk of cancer.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] However, this is under increasing doubt.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Cancer risk can start at the exposure of 1100 mGy.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] It is estimated that the additional radiation from diagnostic X-rays will increase the average person's cumulative risk of getting cancer by age 75 by 0.6–3.0%.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The amount of absorbed radiation depends upon the type of X-ray test and the body part involved.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] CT and fluoroscopy entail higher doses of radiation than do plain X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Each such X-ray would add less than 1 per 1,000,000 to the lifetime cancer risk.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] An abdominal or chest CT would be the equivalent to 2–3 years of background radiation to the whole body, or 4–5 years to the abdomen or chest, increasing the lifetime cancer risk between 1 per 1,000 to 1 per 10,000.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] This is compared to the roughly 40% chance of a US citizen developing cancer during their lifetime.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] For instance, the effective dose to the torso from a CT scan of the chest is about 5 mSv, and the absorbed dose is about 14 mGy.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] A head CT scan (1.5 mSv, 64 mGy) that is performed once with and once without contrast agent, would be equivalent to 40 years of background radiation to the head.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Accurate estimation of effective doses due to CT is difficult with the estimation uncertainty range of about ±19% to ±32% for adult head scans depending upon the method used.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The risk of radiation is greater to a fetus, so in pregnant patients, the benefits of the investigation (X-ray) should be balanced with the potential hazards to the fetus.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] If there is 1 scan in 9 months, it can be harmful to the fetus.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Therefore, women who are pregnant get ultrasounds as their diagnostic imaging because this does not use radiation.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] If there is too much radiation exposure there could be harmful effects on the fetus or the reproductive organs of the mother.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In the US, there are an estimated 62 million CT scans performed annually, including more than 4 million on children.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Avoiding unnecessary X-rays (especially CT scans) reduces radiation dose and any associated cancer risk.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Medical X-rays are a significant source of human-made radiation exposure.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In 1987, they accounted for 58% of exposure from human-made sources in the United States.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] By 2006, however, medical procedures in the United States were contributing much more ionizing radiation than was the case in the early 1980s.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] In 2006, medical exposure constituted nearly half of the total radiation exposure of the U.S. population from all sources.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] The increase is traceable to the growth in the use of medical imaging procedures, in particular computed tomography (CT), and to the growth in the use of nuclear medicine.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Dosage due to dental X-rays varies significantly depending on the procedure and the technology (film or digital).
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Depending on the procedure and the technology, a single dental X-ray of a human results in an exposure of 5 to 40 μSv.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] A full mouth series of X-rays may result in an exposure of up to 60 (digital) to 180 (film) μSv, for a yearly average of up to 400 μSv.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Financial incentives have been shown to have a significant impact on X-ray use with doctors who are paid a separate fee for each X-ray providing more X-rays.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p01] Early photon tomography or EPT (as of 2015) along with other techniques are being researched as potential alternatives to X-rays for imaging applications.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p02] While they fall outside of the wavelengths that compose the visible light spectrum, in special circumstances X-rays can be detected by eye.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p02] Brandes, in an experiment a short time after Röntgen's landmark 1895 paper, reported after dark adaptation and placing his eye close to an X-ray tube, seeing a faint "blue-gray" glow which seemed to originate within the eye itself.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p02] Upon hearing this, Röntgen reviewed his record books and found he too had seen the effect.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p02] When placing an X-ray tube on the opposite side of a wooden door Röntgen had noted the same blue glow, seeming to emanate from the eye itself, but thought his observations to be spurious because he only saw the effect when he used one type of tube.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p02] Later he realized that the tube which had created the effect was the only one powerful enough to make the glow plainly visible and the experiment was thereafter readily repeatable.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p02] The knowledge that X-rays are actually faintly detectable to the dark-adapted naked eye has largely been forgotten today; this is probably due to the desire not to repeat what would now be seen as a recklessly dangerous and potentially harmful experiment with ionizing radiation.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p02] It is not known what exact mechanism in the eye produced the visibility described by Röntgen and Brandes, though Cherenkov radiation caused by the X-rays traveling through the vitreous humor of the eye is a likely explanation.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p02] Other potential explanations for the glow include direct excitation of retinal cells by X-rays, similar to some instances of light flashes seen during experiments regarding cosmic ray visual phenomena.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p02] Though X-rays are otherwise invisible, it is possible to see the ionization of the air molecules if the intensity of the X-ray beam is high enough.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p02] The beamline from the wiggler at the European Synchrotron Radiation Facility is one example of such high intensity.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p02] However, the effect of ionizing radiation on matter (especially living tissue) is more closely related to the amount of energy deposited into them rather than the charge generated.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p02] The equivalent dose is the measure of the biological effect of radiation on human tissue.
[src:ct-imaging/x-ray-p02] For X-rays it is equal to the absorbed dose.
